[Comentario en Core/SQL/update_db_ignition_PS-66980.sql:83 por @Copilot]: The ticket/reference ID in this update header comment doesn’t match the PR/file naming (PS-66980). Keeping the wrong ID will make it harder to trace why this script exists.
[Comentario en Core/SQL/update_db_ignition_PS-66980.sql:110 por @Copilot]: `s_enc_read_user_for_login` performs UPDATEs, but it doesn’t enable `SET XACT_ABORT ON` at the start. Per ProjectSight SQL write-proc conventions, write procedures should start with `SET XACT_ABORT ON` + `SET NOCOUNT ON` to ensure errors abort/rollback work consistently when the proc is executed inside a transaction.
[Comentario en Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/AuthenticationSystem.cs:426 por @Copilot]: The refresh after `UpdateUserFromProfileServiceIfNeededAsync` only copies language/timezone fields back onto `ignitionUser`, but the profile service can also update identity fields like EMail/FirstName/LastName/CompanyName/TrimbleID. Since `user.UpdateFromIgnitionDBUser(...)` uses those properties, the runtime user can still be initialised with stale values until the next refresh.
[Comentario en Core/SQL/base_procs_ignition.sql:6899 por @Copilot]: This write stored procedure still doesn’t enable `SET XACT_ABORT ON` near the start (it only has `SET NOCOUNT ON`). Since this PR is already touching the proc, please add `SET XACT_ABORT ON` to the proc header in `base_procs_ignition.sql` as well (not just the ignition update script) so fresh installs get the same behavior.
[Comentario en Core/Business Layer/DataAccess/AuthenticationSystem.cs:413 por @kcostenbader]: This is incorrect. This will update the user from the profile service on every single request that is made from the web ui. This means 10's of thousands of requests per second. We cannot wait for a call to profile service for every one of these. We need to find a different approach.

